								<h1>State Representative Theresa Mah</h1>

                            <p>
                                <audio src="/audio/en/TheresaMah/TheresahMahArticlePart1.m4a" controls>    
                                    Recording of CCVP article    
                                </audio> 
								<br>
                                <audio src="/audio/en/TheresaMah/TheresahMahOnGrowingChinatown.mp3" controls>    
                                    Recording of CCVP article    
                                </audio> 
                                <br>
                                Theresa Mah was born in San Francisco, California, daughter to immigrant parents. Growing up as an immigrant made her nourish strong views on immigration policies and voters’ rights. This passion led her to become a professor of modern American history and eventually to become a policy advocate and community organizer. <br>
                                <audio src="/audio/en/TheresaMah/MahArticlepart2.m4a" controls>    
                                    Recording of CCVP article    
                                </audio> 
								<br>
                                <audio src="/audio/en/TheresaMah/TheresahMahOnImmigration.mp3" controls>
                                    Recording of CCVP article    
                                </audio> 
                                <br>
                                Theresa Mah on Immigration
                                <br>
                                Q: ​You have familiar experience with immigration, does that change or effect in anyway that you feel about immigration policies?
                                <br>
                                Mah: So the personal connection is what continues to strengthen my views of immigration policies. I have very strong views and also having that personal experience really gives me a lot of insight to what people are experiencing today. When I talk to my constituents it’s less about whether I am Asian versus Latino, but we have the common experience where we are affected by these policies, and so protecting immigrants have been one of my priorities in my policy work and in working with my colleagues in Springfield. This issue is something I will always have a connection to and commitment to because of the personal connection and because of constituents. I feel like I reflect the identity and experiences of my constituents and my experience of growing up in an immigrant family is something that’s really important to me, but also helps me understand the people who live in my district today.
                                <br> <br />
                                Mah’s interest in politics began when she started working with advocacy groups such as the Illinois Coalition for Immigrant and Refugee Rights(ICIRR) and the Coalition for a Better Chinese American Community(CBCAC). While Mah was working with CBCAC her biggest concern was redirecting political power towards the Chinese Community by increasing voter registration and turnout. Other projects were the prevention of the closure of the Chinatown Post-Office and the addition of a Chinatown Library. Additionally, she helped members of the community understand how to reach out to their elected officials and discuss the issues that concern them. 
                                <br> <br />
                                Theresah Mah on Chinatown Museum
                                <audio src="/audio/en/TheresaMah/MahArticlepart3.m4a" controls>    
                                    Recording of CCVP article    
                                </audio> 
								<br>
                                <audio src="/audio/en/TheresaMah/TheresahMahonChinatownMuseum.mp3" controls>    
                                    Recording of CCVP article    
                                </audio> 
                                <br>
                                Q: ​Do you think the Chinatown Museum could help with the lack of cultural connection for Chinese Americans who are teenagers or young adults?
                                <br>
                                Mah: My academic background is in history, so I think there is a role to play for museums such as the Chinese American Museum of Chicago. I think we can support more funding or opportunities or something that would give school children the opportunity to have access to those resources.
                                <br> <br />
                                In order to increase the impact in the community, Mah started working as a senior advisor to former Governor Pat Quinn.  Under his administration, she worked with numerous advocacy groups and legislators with the goal of improving the representation of minorities in state government. Mah’s contribution was crucial when designing the Asian American Employment Plan, the first one proposed in the state. 
                                <br> <br />
                                Theresa Mah on Growing Chinatown
                                <audio src="/audio/en/TheresaMah/MahArticlePart4.m4a" controls>    
                                    Recording of CCVP article    
                                </audio> 
                                <br>
                                Q: ​ Are there any projects you’re working on that has a large impact on Chinatown?
                                <br>
                                Mah: I’m very much involved in the census coming up, and making sure hard to count communities including the Chinese immigrant community gets adequately counted, and that’s something that will have a future impact on Chinatown. The last two censuses resulted in Chinatown language ballots and voting materials because we got adequately counted. After the last census, we got redistricting and we were able to elect a Chinese American member of the legislator. Now it’s just a matter of educating the public and reiterating how important it is to get everyone counted because we have a lot of people in this community that utilize public services and all the funding that comes down in the federal government that comes back to the community. We need to make sure to get all that money because we are a growing Chinatown, but we also have growing needs, and we can’t have less money coming in.
                                <br> <br />
                                Working under former  Governor Pat Quinn administration heavily motivated her to run for Illinois State Representative, becoming the first Asian American to serve in the Illinois House of Representatives. Currently, she is part of the State of Illinois’s Complete Count Commission who is responsible for the 2020 census in the state and guarantees that everyone is accounted for in the state. 

                            </p>
						</div>
